00:37:45.980 --> 00:37:49.640
Call this weird 1-800
number or ask your

00:37:49.640 --> 00:37:52.330
aunt to smuggle some.

00:37:52.330 --> 00:37:56.540
These days, if I wanted to make
a resource section to my

00:37:56.540 --> 00:37:58.620
cookbook, it would be bigger
than the book.

00:37:58.620 --> 00:38:01.300
Because by the time it would
have been published, it would

00:38:01.300 --> 00:38:02.560
have been outdated.

00:38:02.560 --> 00:38:04.970
There's so many brands
that carry

00:38:04.970 --> 00:38:07.340
different cans of things.

00:38:07.340 --> 00:38:11.680
From the pickled jalapenos, to
the chipotles in adobo, to the

00:38:11.680 --> 00:38:15.910
already-cooked beans, to the
salsas, to so many things--

00:38:15.910 --> 00:38:18.060
there's so many brands that by
the time it would have been

00:38:18.060 --> 00:38:21.570
printed, there would be new
companies and people would be

00:38:21.570 --> 00:38:23.520
making many things at home.

00:38:23.520 --> 00:38:27.960
And then if I wanted a list of
stores that sell Mexican

00:38:27.960 --> 00:38:31.725
products, I would spend the
rest of my lifetime.

00:38:31.725 --> 00:38:33.470
And you can find
things online.

00:38:33.470 --> 00:38:37.200
So what I do in the book, and
I really worked very hard at

00:38:37.200 --> 00:38:41.030
it, is describing the
ingredients and giving people

00:38:41.030 --> 00:38:44.030
the knowledge in very
simple, fast ways.

00:38:44.030 --> 00:38:46.570
You know, you have all
these options.

00:38:46.570 --> 00:38:48.450
How do you choose what
you bring home?

00:38:48.450 --> 00:38:51.420
Or if you don't find something
and you really don't want to

00:38:51.420 --> 00:38:53.730
source it-- like piloncillos,
to give you an example.

00:38:53.730 --> 00:38:57.380
It's a fabulous Mexican
ingredient, that I would try

00:38:57.380 --> 00:38:58.600
to find it if I were you.

00:38:58.600 --> 00:38:59.750
Just because I like
it so much.

00:38:59.750 --> 00:39:01.980
I put it in my coffee.

00:39:01.980 --> 00:39:07.600
Piloncillo is the purest
form of cane sugar.

00:39:07.600 --> 00:39:11.100
So when cane is processed, the
first-- it's like extra

00:39:11.100 --> 00:39:13.100
virgin olive oil.

00:39:13.100 --> 00:39:17.920
The first press of cane sugar,
it's this liquid, this cane

00:39:17.920 --> 00:39:19.910
syrup, that is put in cones.

00:39:19.910 --> 00:39:22.050
That's why it's called
pilon, or piloncillo.

00:39:22.050 --> 00:39:24.470
It's put in these cones
and it dries.

00:39:24.470 --> 00:39:29.970
And it has a beautiful,
dark caramel color.

00:39:29.970 --> 00:39:32.770
And it's no preservatives.

00:39:32.770 --> 00:39:34.750
Really not processed.

00:39:34.750 --> 00:39:40.250
It tastes like a little bit like
molasses, like dark brown

00:39:40.250 --> 00:39:44.530
sugar, but with an extra layer
of something rustic.

00:39:44.530 --> 00:39:47.270
It tastes a little bit
like coffee, a

00:39:47.270 --> 00:39:48.060
little bit like nuts.

00:39:48.060 --> 00:39:51.150
It is so rich, I can't
even describe it.

00:39:51.150 --> 00:39:53.990
There's some cookies in here
and recipes that use it.

00:39:53.990 --> 00:39:55.770
You can sub it for
dark brown sugar.

00:39:55.770 --> 00:39:57.190
But you find the piloncillo.

00:39:57.190 --> 00:39:58.970
Now it's easy to find.

00:39:58.970 --> 00:40:03.240
It goes by other names, and
I tell you [INAUDIBLE].

