00:41:26.640 --> 00:41:30.550
So there's a fabulous
pasta in Mexico--

00:41:30.550 --> 00:41:31.320
do you like past?

00:41:31.320 --> 00:41:32.480
Do your friends like pasta?

00:41:32.480 --> 00:41:33.520
OK.

00:41:33.520 --> 00:41:37.010
In Mexico, we call it
pasta seca, when the

00:41:37.010 --> 00:41:38.490
pasta is sort of dry.

00:41:38.490 --> 00:41:41.110
Well, it can have a sauce,
but it's not a soup.

00:41:41.110 --> 00:41:44.390
And we call it sopa aguada
when it has broth.

00:41:44.390 --> 00:41:46.680
And the pasta seca is--

00:41:46.680 --> 00:41:53.910
think of a pasta al pomodoro,
but with a Mexican spin.

00:41:53.910 --> 00:41:57.240
All you need are the
same ingredients--

00:41:57.240 --> 00:42:02.470
pasta, a little bit of oil,
tomatoes, garlic, onion.

00:42:02.470 --> 00:42:04.750
If you can find those
chipotle in adobo

00:42:04.750 --> 00:42:06.350
sauce, it would be fabulous.

00:42:06.350 --> 00:42:08.830
If not, you can use
a jalapeno.

00:42:08.830 --> 00:42:12.100
And so you're going to cook that
pasta the Mexican way.

00:42:14.600 --> 00:42:16.980
We cook pasta many
times like this.

00:42:16.980 --> 00:42:18.440
You're going to break
the pasta--

00:42:18.440 --> 00:42:21.130
either the fettuccine or angel
hair or spaghetti-- whatever

00:42:21.130 --> 00:42:21.960
pasta you have.

00:42:21.960 --> 00:42:23.970
It doesn't even matter.

00:42:23.970 --> 00:42:26.000
Little stars, if you have
little stars, alphabet,

00:42:26.000 --> 00:42:27.080
doesn't matter.

00:42:27.080 --> 00:42:30.580
You're going to cook that pasta
in a saucepan with a

00:42:30.580 --> 00:42:32.300
tiny little bit of oil.

00:42:32.300 --> 00:42:33.820
But the oil has to be hot.

00:42:33.820 --> 00:42:35.780
And you're going
add the pasta.

00:42:35.780 --> 00:42:37.990
You're going to fry
it a little.

00:42:37.990 --> 00:42:42.380
So this is different from the
Italians, what we do to pasta.

00:42:42.380 --> 00:42:45.940
And there's no way that your
pasta will ever be bland.

00:42:45.940 --> 00:42:48.740
Because you're adding
that layer of--

00:42:48.740 --> 00:42:51.040
like when you make roux?

00:42:51.040 --> 00:42:52.880
It's just, you're toasting
the pasta.

00:42:52.880 --> 00:42:56.710
It's adding a layer of
depth and flavor.

00:42:56.710 --> 00:42:59.200
And it just takes
like a minute.

00:42:59.200 --> 00:43:02.930
And then you're going to add the
sauce, which you can make

00:43:02.930 --> 00:43:06.840
it by pureeing tomatoes or with
a can of tomatoes, just

00:43:06.840 --> 00:43:09.070
with some onion and garlic
and the chipotles.

00:43:09.070 --> 00:43:10.990
You're going to add
that to the pasta.

00:43:10.990 --> 00:43:13.670
So instead of boiling the pasta
and then adding the

00:43:13.670 --> 00:43:17.580
sauce, think of an risotto.

00:43:17.580 --> 00:43:18.560
It's sort of the same.

00:43:18.560 --> 00:43:21.420
You fry the pasta for just like
a minute, and then you

00:43:21.420 --> 00:43:22.440
add the sauce.

00:43:22.440 --> 00:43:25.750
And the pasta cooks
in that sauce.

00:43:25.750 --> 00:43:29.750
And so it plumps up and
cooks in sauce until

00:43:29.750 --> 00:43:31.450
it's nice and moist.

00:43:31.450 --> 00:43:33.580
It's incredibly delicious.

00:43:33.580 --> 00:43:37.820
And then you add on top avocado
slices, fresh cheese.

00:43:37.820 --> 00:43:40.660
Don't find Mexican cheese,
queso fresco?

00:43:40.660 --> 00:43:42.500
Use a mild feta.

00:43:42.500 --> 00:43:44.130
And it's really good.

00:43:44.130 --> 00:43:45.070
So that--

00:43:45.070 --> 00:43:46.790
